POLICE Detective Sergeant Bulenganiju Mashiku told the High Court in Bukoba that the third accused facing a murder case for the murder of four people Ngesela Keya Ismail (25) forged a bus ticket dated November 25, 2015. Sergeant Mashiku, who testified as witness (PW) 15 told Judge Lameck Mlacha, who was presiding at the case that he investigated Falcon Bus Services in Bukoba and Dar es Salaam booking offices. He told the court that investigation revealed that the company had issued three books with serial numbers 343201-343600, 343601-344000 and 344001-344400 in 2017. Ngesela had raised the defence of alibi, claiming that he travelled from Bukoba to Dar es Salaam on November 25, 2015 using ticket No 344226, which he claimed was issued by Falcon Bus Company. He told the court that he was arrested on November 21, 2015 and was locked up in a special cell at Kashura Police Resthouse, three kilometres from Bukoba Town until December 2, 2015, when he was taken to court in Kassambya, Missenyi District. He narrated that he was tortured to make a statement at Kassambya Primary Court, but he resisted he was later taken to Kyamunene Forest in Bukoba Rural District, where he was forced to sign several documents at gunpoint. A government chemist, Mr Fidelis Segumba (40), told the court that he conducted DNA tests on several exhibits, which he received from the Kagera regional Crimes' Officer (RCO) and found blood stains that matched those of the accused, who was facing a murder charge offence. Mr Segumba, who testified as PW 9, also tendered as exhibit a Maasai sword and two machetes, which the prosecution claimed were used in mysterious killings of more than 20 people. The killings, most of the victims of which had their throats cut, and which caused much panic amongst Kagera residents, were linked to superstitious beliefs. Three prisoners serving life imprisonment for burning a Roman Catholic Church in Kanazi, Bukoba Rural Rural District, are facing a murder case No 66/2017 for the murder of four people. The convicts were identified as Aliyu Dauda Hassan (36) from Kemondo, Bukoba Rural District, Rashid Mzee Athuman (29), and Ngesela Keya Ismail (24) - both from Rwamishenye Ward in Bukoba Municipal Council. Mr John Kessy, former Bukoba OC CID, on the other hand, told the court that on November 1, 2015, four people, three men and a woman were murdered a single night. He told the court that at about 11.30 pm, he received a phone call and immediately rushed to Ekigoma Hamlet in Katoma Ward, about 15km from Bukoba Town and found two bodies of a man and a woman lying in a pool of blood. According to Mr Kessy, who testified as PW 10, as detectives were examining the bodies, he received another call and rushed to Akilembo Hamlet, where he found two more bodies. He identified the deceased as Kaijage John, Anastela Paschal, Emmanuel Joseph and Evodius Aloys, all from Katoma Ward, Bukoba Rural District.